\label{fig:ranking}
\end{figure}


\section{Discussion}
\label{sec:discussion}

\subsection{What the analysis says about Koide-type quark relations}

Three observations follow.

First, no claim involving search across multiple triples combined with running survives either null model. The full-search $p \approx 0.5$ is not a marginal failure; it is fully consistent with noise under both audited null models, and the conclusion is robust across hierarchy-preserving variants of Model~A, the four correlation choices for Model~B, and three alternative priors.

Second, single-triple claims proposed in prior literature occupy a different position from the full search. The $(c,b,t)$ closure with $m_c$ evaluated at $\mu = m_\tau$ has $p = 0.002$ under Model~A; under hierarchy-preserving variants of Model~A it has $p = 0.004$--$0.007$ (Section~\ref{sec:hierarchy-null}), and under Model~B it has $p \approx 0.15$. It is the only claim in Table~\ref{tab:pvalues} with a noticeably lower bootstrap tail probability than the bulk measurement-noise behaviour, though still not conventionally small.

One feature of this particular claim warrants explicit statement rather than inference from the reference list. The $(c,b,t)$ at $\mu = m_\tau$ hypothesis was published by the present author~\citep{Brilliant2026cbt}, and the analysis reported here began as a sanity check on that prior claim before being extended to the full quark-side search space so that the same criteria could be applied uniformly to proposals by Rivero~\citep{Rivero2011}, Rodejohann and Zhang~\citep{RZ2011}, and Cao~\citep{Cao2012}. The claim is therefore pre-specified relative to the present audit, but it is not pre-registered against future data: it was formulated on the same FLAG/PDG central values the audit uses, and the prior publication is by the present author rather than by a third party. The reported $p = 0.002$ is a multiplicity-corrected statistical characterization of that prior claim under the present audited search space, not an independent confirmation. The temporal-trajectory test introduced in Section~\ref{sec:temporal} is what a forward-looking assessment of this particular claim would draw on.

Third, the knob-isolation analysis (Section~\ref{sec:isolation}) points to running to non-self scales as the degree of freedom that appears to account for most of the noise inflation in the present search space. This does not establish that running is illegitimate; it is a description of how the noise floor of the present audit depends on which degrees of freedom are admitted.

\subsection{Falsifiability of the surviving single-triple claim}

A statistical test against null models speaks to present-day significance. A separate question is whether a claim that survives one null model is robust to anticipated improvements in mass measurements.

The $(c,b,t)$ closure with $m_c$ at $\mu = m_\tau$ has residual $|Q - 2/3| = 5.1 \times 10^{-5}$, currently $0.09\sigma_Q$. The dominant uncertainty contribution is $m_t$ ($\sim 86\%$ of variance). Even at projected FCC-ee precision ($\sigma_{m_t} \approx 0.05$~GeV, a $14\times$ improvement), the residual-to-uncertainty ratio reaches only $\sim 0.2\sigma$, so the closure is unlikely to become testable for exactness within foreseeable experimental precision. It would be falsified if the $m_t$ central value drifts by more than $\sim 0.5$~GeV ($0.7\sigma$ of current uncertainty), or if $m_c(m_c)$ or $m_b(m_b)$ shift by comparable fractions of their uncertainties.

\begin{table}[h]
\centering
\begin{tabular}{llcc}
\toprule
Claim & Key input & Breaks if drift $>$ & Testable when $\sigma <$ \\
\midrule
$(c,b,t)$ at $m_\tau$ & $m_t$ & $0.7\sigma$ ($0.5$~GeV) & not before FCC-ee \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\caption{Drift threshold for the surviving author-pre-specified single-triple claim (see Section~\ref{sec:discussion}).}
\label{tab:drift}
\end{table}

\subsection{Temporal convergence as an additional discriminator}
\label{sec:temporal}

Statistical tests against null models and central-value drift thresholds both speak to present-day significance. A third discriminator, available without any new theory, is whether the residual $|Q - 2/3|$ converges toward zero as measurement precision improves over time. A relation that is exact in nature should produce a residual that shrinks as the propagated $\sigma_Q$ shrinks; a relation that is a coincidence at a particular epoch should produce a residual that remains pinned at its accidental value while $\sigma_Q$ decreases past it.

The original lepton Koide relation is the textbook example. When Koide proposed $Q = 2/3$ in 1981--1983, the world-average $m_\tau$ was $1784.2 \pm 3.2$~MeV, while the value required by the formula given $m_e$ and $m_\mu$ was $1776.97$~MeV. BES measurements published in 1992 and 1996 converged to $1776.96 \pm 0.31$~MeV, and subsequent refinements have remained within $\sim 1\sigma$ of the same value (PDG~2024: $1776.86 \pm 0.12$~MeV). The residual $|Q - 2/3|$ has tracked the shrinking $m_\tau$ uncertainty downward across four decades.

By contrast, the Rivero and Cao quark-side claims that survive Model~A do not show the same pattern. The Rivero $(s, c, b)$ residual at self-scales has remained in the range $|Q - 2/3| \approx 7.5$--$8.2 \times 10^{-3}$ since the FLAG~2013 update introduced $N_f = 2 + 1 + 1$ averages: across FLAG~2013, 2016, 2019, 2021, and~2024 the residual has not budged outside that band while the propagated $\sigma_Q$ has shrunk by roughly a factor of three to its present value of $\sim 5.4 \times 10^{-4}$. The Cao $(c, b, t)$ self-scale residual has shown a similar stability, sitting near $3.5$--$4.7 \times 10^{-3}$ across the same period (slightly increasing as $m_t$ has been refined). In both cases, the ratio of the residual to the propagated $\sigma_Q$ is currently of order $9$--$14$.

\begin{table}[h]
\centering
\small
\begin{tabular}{lcccc}
\toprule
Claim & 2013 $|Q - 2/3|$ & 2024 $|Q - 2/3|$ & 2024 in $\sigma_Q$ & Trend \\
\midrule
Lepton Koide                          & $\sim 10^{-5}$       & $6 \times 10^{-6}$   & $1.0\sigma$  & converging since 1981 \\
Rivero $(s, c, b)$ self [signed]      & $8.2 \times 10^{-3}$ & $7.5 \times 10^{-3}$ & $13.9\sigma$ & stable; non-convergent \\
Cao $(c, b, t)$ self                  & $3.5 \times 10^{-3}$ & $4.7 \times 10^{-3}$ & $8.6\sigma$  & stable / slow drift \\
$(c, b, t)$ at $\mu = m_\tau$         & ---                  & $5.1 \times 10^{-5}$ & $0.09\sigma$ & not yet assessable \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\caption{Temporal stability of $|Q - 2/3|$ for the four most-discussed Koide-type claims. Lepton Koide is the only one whose residual has tracked decreasing $\sigma_Q$ downward. Rivero and Cao have residuals an order of magnitude or more larger than current $\sigma_Q$ that have not converged with measurement improvements. The $(c, b, t)$ at $\mu = m_\tau$ claim was first identified post-hoc on current FLAG/PDG central values~\citep{Brilliant2026cbt}, so its present small residual carries no temporal information; meaningful assessment requires future independent measurement updates.}
\label{tab:temporal-summary}
\end{table}

The $(c, b, t)$ at $\mu = m_\tau$ claim cannot yet be assessed by this criterion. It was identified post-hoc on the current FLAG/PDG central values~\citep{Brilliant2026cbt}, so its present small residual reflects the conditions under which it was selected and contains no information about whether the relation is exact. As $m_c$, $m_b$, and (to a smaller extent) $m_t$ are refined in subsequent FLAG and PDG releases, the residual will either converge toward zero (consistent with an exact relation) or drift away (consistent with selection on a particular set of central values). The drift thresholds in Table~\ref{tab:drift} provide a quantitative version of the same statement.


\subsection{A geometric extension treated separately}

A second class of Koide-type claim involves geometric constructions on the lepton triple rather than algebraic relations among quark masses. One such construction---the squared outer Soddy curvature of the Koide-saturating lepton triple, evaluated at the scale $\Sigma m_\ell$, compared against $m_s$---has been examined in a separate preprint~\citep{Brilliant2026strange}. Applying the framework of the present note to that construction is a worthwhile exercise but raises issues distinct from the quark-only search treated here, including a careful audit of geometric degrees of freedom and a parametric bootstrap centred on $m_s$ rather than on the lepton inputs. We defer that analysis to follow-up work and note here only that the same two-null-model framework is the appropriate tool.

\subsection{Limitations}

The search space is finite, discrete, and physically interpretable; it does not exhaust all conceivable Koide-type formulations. A continuous scale scan would inflate the trial count and the implied LEE penalty without bound, so the present discrete audit should be read as a lower-complexity benchmark, not an exhaustive accounting. We do not vary the algebraic target ($Q = 2/3$ throughout), the mass scheme ($\overline{\text{MS}}$ only), or the fermion content (no neutrinos, no boson masses).

Approximately one-third of random-spectrum Model~A draws fail in CRunDec because of pathological QCD configurations and are excluded; these dropped draws have systematically larger best residuals (median and KS evidence) than the retained draws, which under the stochastic-dominance assumption discussed in Section~\ref{sec:loss-bias} biases reported Model~A $p$-values upward. The reported values are therefore upper bounds under that assumption, and the qualitative ranking is unaffected.

Robustness of the two null models is examined in Section~\ref{sec:robustness}, where the running implementation, the random-spectrum prior family, the assumption of uncorrelated FLAG/PDG uncertainties, and the loss-rate bias are each tested.


\section{Conclusion}
\label{sec:conclusion}

Under the two null models audited here, evaluation at non-self renormalization scales appears to account for most of the noise inflation in the present search space. At full search freedom, both a generic random-spectrum reference null and a measurement-noise null around the observed spectrum reproduce the observed closures with $p \approx 0.5$. Robustness checks (Section~\ref{sec:robustness}) indicate that this result does not depend on the running implementation, on the choice of prior family within the tested range, on plausible correlation structure in the FLAG/PDG uncertainties, or on the bias introduced by dropped numerical draws.

Pre-specified single-triple claims occupy an intermediate position. The $(c,b,t)$ closure at $\mu = m_\tau$ has $p = 0.002$ under Model~A and $p \approx 0.15$ under Model~B; under hierarchy-preserving variants of Model~A it sits at $p = 0.004$--$0.007$; under the four correlation choices for Model~B and three alternative Model~A priors it stays in the same neighbourhood. It is the only single-triple claim with a noticeably lower Model~B tail probability than the bulk measurement-noise behaviour, though still not conventionally small. The claim was published by the present author in~\citep{Brilliant2026cbt} prior to the present audit, and the audit began as a sanity check on that claim before being extended to the full quark-side search space; the present analysis therefore provides a multiplicity-corrected statistical characterization of a prior claim by the same author, not an independent confirmation. The temporal trajectory of its residual across future FLAG/PDG releases (Section~\ref{sec:temporal}, Table~\ref{tab:drift}) is what a subsequent forward-looking evaluation would draw on.

The analysis, all code, all seeds, and the audited trial list are in the repository~\citep{RepoMC}.


\section*{Computational note}

All computations are reproducible from~\citep{RepoMC}. Search space: \texttt{search\_space.json} ($12{,}960$ trials, audited in \texttt{trial\_list\_complete.csv}). Running: four-loop $\overline{\text{MS}}$ via \texttt{CRunDec}~\citep{CRunDec}, with thresholds computed from the input mass spectrum (SM values for Models~A and~B baseline; perturbed values for bootstrap variants; random values for random-spectrum draws). Inputs: FLAG~2024, PDG~2024.

Random-spectrum MC (Model~A): $10{,}000$ experiments per prior variant, full CRunDec on every draw. Bootstrap MC (Model~B): $2{,}000$ experiments per correlation variant, full CRunDec on every draw, with perturbations applied uniformly to all claims including self-scale-only claims (an earlier draft implementation evaluated self-scale claims at unperturbed central values; this has been corrected and the corrected values are reported here). Surrogate validation: $500$ paired draws comparing surrogate to full CRunDec (the surrogate failed validation and was not used in the final analysis). Hierarchy-preserving null: $10{,}000$ experiments per variant. Loss-bias check: distribution comparison on $3{,}269$ dropped draws against $6{,}731$ retained draws under surrogate running. All seeds documented in the repository.


